_become_a_trainer_for_Care_Certificate_Standard_3_Duty_of_Care_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1692707435 320w" width="2000" height="1415" alt="Why you should become a trainer for Care Certificate Standard 3 Duty of Care - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Why you should become a trainer for Care Certificate Standard 3 Duty of Care - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-leSONj uTJGF pf-15_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-95b8" data-category="Generic Content" data-name="Matcha" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jNHqnW kXSKNz pf-16_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-cqJhZP gRKDwp"><div class="sc-iAKWXU lesjfG pf-17_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-eySxxw fIKYYX pf-18_"><p class="sc-dMOJrz cGFGtP pf-19_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-21_">The Care Certificate in England outlines the expected knowledge, skills, and behaviours of healthcare support workers and adult social care workers. Its purpose is to ensure that these workers possess the necessary competencies to provide exceptional care and support to patients and service users. <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/products/care-certificate-standard-3-train-the-trainer-trainer-pack?variant=31845740281925" target="_blank"><i><span style="color: rgb(0, 102, 204);">Standard 3 of the Care Certificate</span></i></a> centres around "Duty of Care," which we will discuss in this blog post and emphasise the significance of receiving proper training in this area.</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-22_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-24_">What is duty of care?</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/What_is_duty_of_care_-_train_the_trainer_standard_3_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707542" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/What_is_duty_of_care_-_train_the_trainer_standard_3_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707542 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/What_is_duty_of_care_-_train_the_trainer_standard_3_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1692707542 320w" width="2649" height="1740" alt="What is duty of care - train the trainer standard 3 - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="What is duty of care - train the trainer standard 3 - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-leSONj uTJGF pf-25_"/><p class="sc-dMOJrz cGFGtP pf-26_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-28_">As a healthcare support worker or adult social care worker in England, Standard 3 of the Care Certificate highlights your responsibility to ensure the well-being and safety of all individuals receiving care and support in your workplace. This duty of care is a legal obligation that applies as soon as someone receives care or treatment, and it cannot be disregarded. Negligent behaviour that breaches this duty may result in legal action. <br><br>Your duty of care extends to both individuals receiving care and to your colleagues in the community. It is essential to have the necessary knowledge and skills to fulfil your duty of care while also recognising its limitations and not exceeding your role's boundaries. This duty of care is an integral part of the healthcare support worker and adult social care worker's code of conduct and is most likely included in your job description. </span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-29_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-31_">Understanding how duty of care contributes to safe practice </span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Understanding_how_duty_of_care_contributes_to_safe_practice_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707667" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Understanding_how_duty_of_care_contributes_to_safe_practice_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707667 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Understanding_how_duty_of_care_contributes_to_safe_practice_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1692707667 320w" width="2336" height="1557" alt="Understanding how duty of care contributes to safe practice - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Understanding how duty of care contributes to safe practice - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-leSONj uTJGF pf-32_"/><p class="sc-dMOJrz cGFGtP pf-33_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-35_">It's important to truly understand the concept of duty of care and not simply acknowledge it. This principle is crucial for providing safe and effective care. Managers should educate their staff on the legal and ethical responsibilities that come with this duty. It's important for staff to understand that their actions directly impact the safety and well-being of the individuals they care for.<br><br>The <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/train-the-trainer-courses-and-qualifications" target="_blank"><i><span style="color: rgb(0, 102, 204);">train-the-trainer</span></i></a> model can be utilised to provide all the relevant legislation, which sets out the legal framework for duty of care. This includes information such as risk assessment, hazard prevention, and creating a safe work environment, all of which are integral components of duty of care.<br><br>Understanding duty of care also involves recognising the challenges that may arise when it intersects with an individual's rights. Trainers can guide staff through scenarios and discussions that illuminate the fine line between ensuring safety and respecting individual rights. Ultimately, a trainer will teach their staff to grasp the connection between duty of care and safe practice.<br> </span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-36_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-38_">Understanding the support available for addressing dilemmas</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Understanding_the_support_available_for_addressing_dilemmas_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707778" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Understanding_the_support_available_for_addressing_dilemmas_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707778 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Understanding_the_support_available_for_addressing_dilemmas_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1692707778 320w" width="2274" height="1516" alt="Understanding the support available for addressing dilemmas - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Understanding the support available for addressing dilemmas - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-leSONj uTJGF pf-39_"/><p class="sc-dMOJrz cGFGtP pf-40_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-42_">It is important for managers to ensure that their teams know where to seek guidance when faced with difficult situations. This involves being familiar with internal policies, protocols, and external support systems.<br><br>With access to materials in the train-the-trainer course, you will underscore the importance of compliance with the Management of Health and Safety Regulations 1999. These regulations mandate the establishment of procedures for recording, reporting, and evaluating serious incidents. Moreover, they necessitate taking measures to prevent these incidents from recurring. By adhering to these regulations, staff contribute to a safer care environment and have the necessary support structures in place when dilemmas arise.<br><br>Addressing conflicts and dilemmas effectively is another crucial aspect of duty of care. Trainers are guided on how to provide in-depth training on how to approach and manage these situations. This involves explaining the essential steps to take when conflicts arise, which may include communication strategies, mediation techniques, and involving higher authorities when necessary.</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-43_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-45_">Dealing with comments and complaints</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_Comments_and_Complaints_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707858" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_Comments_and_Complaints_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707858 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_Comments_and_Complaints_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1692707858 320w" width="2453" height="1637" alt="Dealing with Comments and Complaints - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Dealing with Comments and Complaints - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-leSONj uTJGF pf-46_"/><p class="sc-bvFjSx yVjXo pf-47_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Comments and complaints are inevitable in any care setting. Every person under your care has the right to voice their concerns, which is also stated in the Care Quality Commission (CQC) fundamental standards. The care provider must have a system in place to receive and respond to complaints. They should conduct a thorough investigation and take action if necessary. Managers must educate their staff on how to handle complaints constructively, and the staff should be knowledgeable in reporting procedures to the appropriate person.<br><br>As a trainer, it's important to understand the Local Authority Social Services and NHS Complaints (England) Regulations 2009, which govern health and social care complaints. You should be able to explain the procedures that should be followed depending on the specific workplace. Regardless of the size of your place of work, there should be a complaint structure in place that should be handled in accordance with the organisation's agreed ways of working. While smaller workplaces may not have written procedures, they will still have agreed ways of working for managing complaints.</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-49_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-51_">Dealing with incidents, errors, and near misses</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_incidents_errors_and_near_misses_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707935" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_incidents_errors_and_near_misses_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692707935 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_incidents_errors_and_near_misses_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1692707935 320w" width="2000" height="1333" alt="Dealing with incidents, errors, and near misses - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Dealing with incidents, errors, and near misses - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-leSONj uTJGF pf-52_"/><p class="sc-bvFjSx yVjXo pf-53_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Making mistakes is a natural part of being human, but in adult social care, they can have significant consequences. To avoid such situations, managers need to ensure that their staff understands the significance of reporting incidents, mistakes, and near misses. It is also essential to emphasise the role of learning and improvement in preventing such incidents from happening again in the future.<br><br>Ensuring your staff are trained to standard 3 of the Care Certificate can greatly reduce the likelihood of mistakes caused by factors such as insufficient knowledge, poor communication, or failure to share important information. Trainers should emphasise the importance of adhering to the reporting of injuries guidelines. Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrences Regulations 2013 (RIDDOR) requires specific workplace accidents, occupational diseases, and dangerous occurrences to be reported to the Health and Safety Executive (HSE). COSHH mandates that employers assess the risks associated with harmful substances and take necessary precautions. By complying with these regulations, staff can help create a safer care environment and fulfil their legal obligations.<br><br>Trainers should offer clear instructions on how to document and report these incidents, stressing the importance of accuracy and promptness. It's important to prioritise the well-being of those involved and address their immediate needs after an incident. Your workplace should have a form for recording incidents, accidents, and near misses that should be filled out.</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-55_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-57_">Dealing with confrontation and difficult situations</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_confrontation_and_difficult_situations_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692708034" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_confrontation_and_difficult_situations_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1692708034 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Dealing_with_confrontation_and_difficult_situations_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1692708034 320w" width="2000" height="1333" alt="Dealing with confrontation and difficult situations - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Dealing with confrontation and difficult situations - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-leSONj uTJGF pf-58_"/><p class="sc-bvFjSx yVjXo pf-59_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">In the challenging environment of adult social care, staff can encounter difficult situations that require de-escalation and effective communication. Managers should provide training on recognising signs of tension, employing verbal and non-verbal communication techniques, and maintaining professionalism in high-pressure situations.<br><br>By adopting the <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/train-the-trainer-courses-and-qualifications" target="_blank"><i><span style="color: rgb(0, 102, 204);">train-the-trainer</span></i></a> approach, trainers can stress the importance of adhering to the Provisions and Use of Work Equipment Regulations 1998 (PUWER). These regulations stipulate that those in charge of work equipment must ensure that it is fit for purpose, properly maintained, and only operated by competent and knowledgeable personnel. This promotes safety and emphasises that contraventions of these regulations are considered criminal acts in the UK, underscoring the need to report any violations immediately.<br><br>Using the Standard 3 Care Certificate pack, you can instruct your staff to recognise potential triggers and warning signs related to individual preferences, communication barriers, and environmental stressors. Trainers will use various scenarios to help staff grasp these factors better. Furthermore, they will learn how to report any workplace confrontations appropriately. Trainers will provide clear instructions on the necessary steps to take when reporting confrontations, including who to report to, the required documentation, and the importance of accurate and timely reporting.</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-61_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-bjztik hIbmEr pf-63_">About the Care Certificate Standard 3 trainer pack</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/About_the_Care_Certificate_Standard_3_trainer_pack_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg